snippet.textDisplay: I love how in the past child rearing was just an everyday part of life and now it's some kind of cult mystery that only those born with the knowledge somehow know. Seriously world WTF happened to us, it's just children, feed them when they cry, let them roam around, don't take your eyes off them while they play, let them sleep. rinse and repeat not hard, my first kid was easy and not scary, just adult up and raise them the best you can, if your child is healthy, getting plenty of play time, food, sleep, and doesn't get killed because of your lazy ass then you can officially call yourself a good parent. Throw away all these stupid help books, they are dulling your natural instincts, last time I checked you don't need a book to explain to a kid that everyone in this world takes a shit, is into this wonderful thing called sex (for you who have teenagers out there), And that stupidity will most likely make you end up in an early grave, Yeah you need thousands of books on how to raise children instead of just good old common sense, if something seems wrong with your kid, take them to the hospital if you are not sure, simple, if you can't afford to take your kid to the hospital then sorry to say that you probably should not have had children until you are able to financially raise one. (U.S. average cost to raise one child to adulthood with a college education 400,000 to 500,000 dollars). If what is happening on the TV, or your Social Media, or the Internet is more interesting than taking care of your offspring, then you should probably grow up a bit before having children. The basic requirements to being a parent are 1) being able to afford having children, House, medical expenses/ insurances, food (preferably healthy), decent area to grow up in (location is important so that you don't become a thug), good education (or the best that you are able to get, schools are good but a parents ability to properly teach and help children learn is just as important), unforeseen expenses. 2) having a job that can assure your child has the best chance to grow up in the best environment possible (don't be that bum on the couch that does nothing). 3) Having a general and pure interest in your child and what they are doing, learning, and behaving. 3) don't be the best friend, you are a parent, so act like it, if your child fucks up (and they will) they need to know that you will come down on them, you don't need to be physical after all the western world thrives on the concept of guilt unlike the Asian culture of shame. Anything after this is just extra bonus points on you for going above and beyond the call of parenthood. Yeah being a parent is about sacrifice and compromise much like getting married, so if you become a parent, stop bitching about how hard it is and roll up your sleeves and get to work, look at your child as building a custom roadster or yacht, yeah it's going to be expensive and a shit ton of hard work but afterwards you can take it to the car or boat show with pride and show off how fucking awesome it is and everyone will be in awe of your accomplishment and the beauty and ferocity of the finished product.
